## Migration: `TimedExecutor` â†’ .NET 8

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` and `ThreadAbortException` are also gone. The fix is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Task-based model uses the thread pool; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` | CTS handles the timeout; no need for a manual join deadline |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation â€” the token auto-cancels after the timeout |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | The new exception type thrown by cancellation-aware APIs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No equivalent needed; cooperative model doesn't forcibly inject exceptions |

### Critical Pitfall: Work Must Cooperate

The **fundamental paradigm shift** is that cancellation is no longer preemptive â€” your `work` delegate **must check the token**. If it doesn't, cancellation won't interrupt it.

```csharp
// âťŚ BAD â€” this will NOT be interrupted by cancellation
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    Thread.Sleep(60_000); // ignores the token
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// âś… GOOD â€” cooperates with cancellation
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    ct.WaitHandle.WaitOne(60_000);   // wakes on cancel
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// âś… GOOD â€” loop with checkpoint
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return results;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If You Cannot Modify the Work (Uncooperative Code)

If the delegate calls code you don't control (third-party library, long native call), **no in-process mechanism can forcibly stop it**. Move it to a child process and use `Process.Kill()`:

```csharp
// Last resort for truly uncooperative code
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

### Keeping the Old Signature (Backward Compatibility Shim)

If callers can't be updated immediately, add an overload â€” but document that **it cannot actually cancel uncooperative work**:

```csharp
// Shim: fire-and-forget semantics â€” the work may keep running!
[Obsolete("Use the CancellationToken overload for true cancellation.")]
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    return ExecuteWithTimeout(ct => work(), timeout);
}
```

### Checklist

- âś… No `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `ResetAbort`
- âś… No `SYSLIB0006` warnings
- âś… `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed (`using`)
- âś… Timeout surfaces as `TimeoutException` (same behavior)
- âś… Inner exceptions still wrapped in `AggregateException`
- âš ď¸Ź **All work delegates must be updated** to accept and check `CancellationToken`
